Bottom shrimp trawling in 
Brazil
is an important socio-economic activity, which was responsible for catches of approximately 38.7 thousand tonnes of marine shrimps in 2011 off Brazilian waters (MPA, 2011). In the state of 
Sergipe
, shrimp catches amounted to approximately 1.3 thousand tonnes in 2014 (

). However, bottom shrimp trawlers are considered predatory, especially due to the low selectivity leading to high catches of non-target species that end up discarded. This causes a serious environmental problem, as many of these species may be ecologically important in the food chain (

) or may be juveniles of commercially important species (

), even though they do not have economic importance (

; 

). FAO data indicate that 1,865 thousand tonnes of by-catch are discarded in relation to 1,126 thousand tonnes of shrimps landed in the world (1992–2001 period), with an average discard rate of 62% (

). Discarded by-catch includes several species of fish, crustaceans, mollusks, cnidarians, and echinoderms of no commercial importance (

), which under continuous fishing pressure are subject to several environmental problems (

; 

; 

).

In surveys conducted along the Brazilian coast, many species are caught as by-catch in shrimp fisheries: 216 species off Santa Catarina (
), 258 species off São Paulo (
), 77 species off Espírito Santo (
), and 79 species of only crustaceans between Sergipe and Alagoas (Santos et al. , 2016). In these studies, the presence of brachyuran crabs is significant, indicating this group is widely distributed along the Brazilian coast and has been probably impacted by shrimp trawlers. One of the brachyurans with the highest catch rates is the flecked box crab
Hepatus pudibundus (Herbst, 1785)
(Severino-Rodrigues et al. , 2002;
;
;
).


Hepatus pudibundus

belongs to the 
Aethridae
and occurs in the Western Atlantic Ocean, from 
Georgia
(
USA
) to 
Rio Grande do Sul
(
Brazil
), on muddy or sandy areas with biodetritus and up to 
160 m
depth (

). Some of the studies for this species off the southeastern-southern regions in 
Brazil
reported its presence as by-catch and/or analysed the population structure and length at first maturity (

; 

; 

; 

), population dynamics (Sardá 
et al.
, 2013; 

), reproductive cycle (

), natural feeding habits (

), distribution, abundance and reproductive biology (

